SIMPLE: peer
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Peer
<hw>Peer</hw> <pr>(p⟦emac⟧r)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Peered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Peering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF. <ets>parir</ets>,
<ets>pareir</ets> equiv. to F. <ets>para⟦icir⟧tre</ets> to appear, L.
<ets>parere</ets>. Cf. <er>Appear</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To come
in sight; to appear.</def> <mark>[Poetic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So honor <qex>peereth</qex> in the meanest habit.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>See how his gorget <qex>peers</qex> above his gown!</q>
<rj><qau>B. Jonson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[Perh. a different word; cf. OE. <ets>piren</ets>,
LG. <ets>piren</ets>. Cf. <er>Pry</er> to peep.]</ety> <def>To look
narrowly or curiously or intently; to peep; <as>as, the <ex>peering</ex>
day</as>.</def> <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Peering</qex> in maps for ports, and piers, and roads.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As if through a dungeon grate he <qex>peered</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Coleridge.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Peer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Peer
<hw>Peer</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>per</ets>, OF.
<ets>per</ets>, F. <ets>pair</ets>, fr. L. <ets>par</ets> equal. Cf.
<er>Apparel</er>, <er>Pair</er>, <er>Par</er>, <pos>n.</pos>,
<er>Umpire</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One of the same rank, quality,
endowments, character, etc.; an equal; a match; a mate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In song he never had his <qex>peer</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Shall they consort only with their <qex>peers</qex>?</q>
<rj><qau>I. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A comrade; a companion; a fellow; an
associate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He all his <qex>peers</qex> in beauty did surpass.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A nobleman; a member of one of the five degrees of
the British nobility, namely, duke, marquis, earl, viscount, baron;
<as>as, a <ex>peer</ex> of the realm</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A noble <qex>peer</qex> of mickle trust and power.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>House of Peers</b></col>, <col><b>The
Peers</b></col></mcol>, <cd>the British House of Lords. See
<er>Parliament</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Spiritual peers</b></col>, <cd>the
bishops and archibishops, or lords spiritual, who sit in the House of
Lords.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Peer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Peer
<hw>Peer</hw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To make equal in rank.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Heylin.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Peer</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Peer
<hw>Peer</hw> <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To be, or to assume to be,
equal.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Peerage</ent>⟦br⟧
